\begin_layout Subsection
Rules Engine
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could also use a rule engine (such as drools), give the client the ability
 to define the rules that he would like to apply, and execute those rules
 when selecting the employees population (reading step), and in the processing
 step as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As one can notice, this solution is very limited to the number of possibilities
 that the client can choose from (finite list of rules) and would be able
 to define very simple and basic operations, simple filtering in the reading
 step, and basic math operations in the processing step.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The client would have no control over the reading and writing step, which
 is another huge limitation, nor over the data structure to be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Custom Code Injection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We decided to go Java's way, by defining a specification, and let the vendor
 (client in our case) implement this specification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JSR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The solution we went for is to create two separate JARs, a JAR (Java ARchive)
 is a package file used to aggregate Java class files: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Specifications Jar: Also called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Template Jar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which will be handed to the client, where he must implement it in order
 to write his own business logic.
 This jar will contain a set of interfaces and abstract classes, for each
 of the three steps mentioned above.
 The classes that the client wrote, would then be autowired in a runner
 jar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Runner jar: Will hold the batch steps definitions and configurations and
 would execute the methods that has been wrote by the client in our environment,
 by autowiring/injecting the classes that have been implemented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After implementing the Template JAR, where the custom code will reside,
 the client only needs to upload the generated JAR, through the frontend
 application form, and specifies a set of options, such the datasource that
 would be used in the reading step, whether the job should be scheduled,
 number of retries ..., he can then manage those jobs, by starting them, stopping,
 monitoring, view generated reports, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will go through the job configuration options in details in later chapters.
\end_layout

